<section xml:id="C18.S13">
<title>Continued Fractions</title>        
  
<para xml:id="C18.S13.p1">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="1" xml:id="C18.S13.p1.s1">
We use the terminology of §1.12(ii).
</sentence>

</para>
 
<paragraph xml:id="C18.S13.Px1">
<title>Chebyshev</title>    
<para xml:id="C18.S13.Px1.p1">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="2" xml:id="C18.S13.Px1.p1.s1">
 <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C18.S13.Px1.p1.m1">T_{n}\left(x\right)</Math> is the denominator of the <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C18.S13.Px1.p1.m2">n</Math> th approximant to: <Math equation-number="18.13.1" mode="display" xml:id="C18.S13.E1">\cfrac{-1}{x+\cfrac{-1}{2x+\cfrac{-1}{2x+}}}\cdots,</Math> and <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C18.S13.Px1.p1.m3">U_{n}\left(x\right)</Math> is the denominator of the <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C18.S13.Px1.p1.m4">n</Math> th approximant to: <Math equation-number="18.13.2" mode="display" xml:id="C18.S13.E2">\cfrac{-1}{2x+\cfrac{-1}{2x+\cfrac{-1}{2x+}}}\cdots</Math>.
</sentence>

</para>
 
</paragraph>
 
<paragraph xml:id="C18.S13.Px2">
<title>Legendre</title>    
<para xml:id="C18.S13.Px2.p1">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="3" xml:id="C18.S13.Px2.p1.s1">
 <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C18.S13.Px2.p1.m1">P_{n}\left(x\right)</Math> is the denominator of the <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C18.S13.Px2.p1.m2">n</Math> th approximant to: <Math equation-number="18.13.3" mode="display" xml:id="C18.S13.E3">\cfrac{a_{1}}{x+\cfrac{-\frac{1}{2}}{\frac{3}{2}x+\cfrac{-\frac{2}{3}}{\frac{5 }{3}x+\cfrac{-\frac{3}{4}}{\frac{7}{4}x+}}}}\cdots,</Math> where <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C18.S13.Px2.p1.m3">a_{1}</Math> is an arbitrary nonzero constant.
</sentence>

</para>
 
</paragraph>
 
<paragraph xml:id="C18.S13.Px3">
<title>Laguerre</title>    
<para xml:id="C18.S13.Px3.p1">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="4" xml:id="C18.S13.Px3.p1.s1">
 <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C18.S13.Px3.p1.m1">L_{n}\left(x\right)</Math> is the denominator of the <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C18.S13.Px3.p1.m2">n</Math> th approximant to: <Math equation-number="18.13.4" mode="display" xml:id="C18.S13.E4">\cfrac{a_{1}}{1-x+\cfrac{-\frac{1}{2}}{\frac{1}{2}(3-x)+\cfrac{-\frac{2}{3}}{ \frac{1}{3}(5-x)+\cfrac{-\frac{3}{4}}{\frac{1}{4}(7-x)+}}}}\cdots,</Math> where <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C18.S13.Px3.p1.m3">a_{1}</Math> is again an arbitrary nonzero constant.
</sentence>

</para>
 
</paragraph>
 
<paragraph xml:id="C18.S13.Px4">
<title>Hermite</title>    
<para xml:id="C18.S13.Px4.p1">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="5" xml:id="C18.S13.Px4.p1.s1">
 <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C18.S13.Px4.p1.m1">H_{n}\left(x\right)</Math> is the denominator of the <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C18.S13.Px4.p1.m2">n</Math> th approximant to: <Math equation-number="18.13.5" mode="display" xml:id="C18.S13.E5">\cfrac{1}{2x+\cfrac{-2}{2x+\cfrac{-4}{2x+\cfrac{-6}{2x+}}}}\cdots</Math>.
</sentence>

</para>
 
<para xml:id="C18.S13.Px4.p2">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="6" xml:id="C18.S13.Px4.p2.s1">
See also Cuyt et al. (2008, pp. 91–99).
</sentence>

</para>

  
</paragraph>
 
</section>
